OK, I think I might have found the "intended" solution—or at least a solution that follows the hint. Hopefully it does not contain any errors... As Martin Brandenburg points out, $k/L$ is a finite extension; since we're in characteristic $0$ , it is actually a Galois extension, and the fact that $L$ is the fixed field of $\sigma$ implies that the Galois group is generated by $\sigma$ . So $k/L$ is a cyclic extension with Galois group $\mathbb{Z}/p$ . It follows that $N_{k/L}(\zeta) = 1$ , so we may apply Hilbert 90 to get some $\alpha\in k$ such that $\sigma(\alpha) = \zeta\alpha$ . In particular, $\alpha\notin L$ . Since $k$ is algebraically closed, it contains some $\beta$ with $\beta^p=\alpha$ , and \begin{equation*}
N_{k/L}(\beta) = \prod_{j=0}^{p-1} \sigma^j(\beta) = \alpha\prod_{j=0}^{p-1}\frac{\sigma^j(\beta)}{\beta}.
\end{equation*} Now observe that \begin{equation*}
\left(\prod_{j=0}^{p-1}\frac{\sigma^j(\beta)}{\beta}\right)^p = \prod_{j=0}^{p-1}\frac{\sigma^j(\alpha)}{\alpha} = \prod_{j=0}^{p-1}\zeta^j = \zeta^{p(p-1)/2}= 1,
\end{equation*} so in fact \begin{equation*}
\prod_{j=0}^{p-1}\frac{\sigma^j(\beta)}{\beta} = \zeta^j
\end{equation*} for some $0\leq j\leq p-1$ ; in particular, this product is in $L$ . But \begin{equation*}
N_{k/L}(\beta) = \alpha\prod_{j=0}^{p-1}\frac{\sigma^j(\beta)}{\beta} \in L.
\end{equation*} So $\alpha\in L$ as well, which is a contradiction with our choice of $\alpha$ . Hence no such $\sigma$ can exist.
